{"key":"post-8608785","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8608785</id>\n<content>I prefer to use the needle or scalpel as soon as it's 'cool' without wiping.&amp;nbsp; Normally, a drop or two of solution can be squeezed out from a red hot needle and it's ready to use.&amp;nbsp; If it's a scalpel, the fist swipe through the petri dish or mushroom flesh sizzles it enough to cool for a sterile transfer.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;After a scalpel or needle has been repeatly heated, they don't really turn red anymore.&amp;nbsp; I've noticed this for years.&amp;nbsp; That's usually when it's become dull anyway, so it's time to change.&amp;nbsp; Brand new needles and scalpel blades will turn red hot very quickly.&amp;nbsp; If you're using a very old blade or needle, simply hold it over the flame for 15 to 30 seconds and that should take care of any bacteria present.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>8608793</next>\n<prev>8608782</prev>\n<first>8608591</first>\n<last>8610236</last>\n<when>1215554357</when>\n<utime>07/09/08 12:59 AM</utime>\n</post>"}